  "local_port": 33020,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What is the best app to learn English?",
  "response": "The \"best\" app for learning English can vary depending on individual learning styles and needs. However, some highly recommended apps for learning English include:\n\n1. **Duolingo**:\n   - **Pros**: Free, gamified learning experience, covers a wide range of topics and skills, good for beginners.\n   - **Cons**: Limited in-depth grammar explanations, may not be suitable for advanced learners.\n\n2. **Babbel**:\n   - **Pros**: Focuses on conversational skills, includes grammar lessons, suitable for various proficiency levels.\n   - **Cons**: Requires a subscription, less gamified than Duolingo.\n\n3. **Rosetta Stone**:\n   - **Pros**: Immersive learning experience, strong focus on pronunciation, suitable for all levels.\n   - **Cons**: Expensive, less emphasis on grammar explanations.\n\n4. **Memrise**:\n   - **Pros**: Uses spaced repetition for vocabulary learning, includes video clips of native speakers, fun and engaging.\n   - **Cons**: Less structured than some other apps, may not cover grammar as comprehensively.\n\n5. **HelloTalk**:\n   - **Pros**: Language exchange platform, allows direct communication with native English speakers, good for practicing conversational skills.\n   - **Cons**: Requires initiative to find and engage with language partners, may not be suitable for beginners without a basic foundation.\n\n6. **FluentU**:\n   - **Pros**: Uses real-world videos like movie trailers and music videos for learning, interactive captions, good for cultural context.\n   - **Cons**: Can be expensive, may not be as effective for absolute beginners.\n\n7. **Busuu**:\n   - **Pros**: Offers a structured learning path, includes grammar lessons and vocabulary exercises, provides feedback from native speakers.\n   - **Cons**: Subscription-based, the free version has limited features.\n\nEach of these apps has its strengths and may be more suitable depending on your specific needs, such as whether you're focusing on grammar, vocabulary, pronunciation, or conversational skills. It's often a good idea to try out a few to see which one works best for you.",
